    language: 'EN', year: 1988, rating: 4.5, pages: 208,
    publisher: 'HarperOne', isbn: '978-0-06-231609-7',
    description: 'Santiago is a young Andalusian shepherd who has a recurring dream of finding treasure near the Egyptian pyramids. When an encounter with a mysterious old king who claims to be the King of Salem convinces him to sell his flock and cross the sea to Africa, he begins a journey that will take him through the Sahara, into the desert, and eventually to an understanding of what the alchemists called the Soul of the World.\n\nCoelho wrote The Alchemist in two weeks, convinced he was transcribing something that already existed. It is a novel of ideas rather than plot — a philosophical fable about the nature of personal destiny, the value of pursuing one\'s deepest desire, and the way that the universe conspires in favour of those who have the courage to follow their own path. The language is simple, almost parable-like, and deliberately universal.\n\nFew books have sold as many copies as The Alchemist, and its reception divides readers sharply. Critics find it simplistic; its admirers find it quietly transformative. What is undeniable is that Coelho touches something in his readers that more sophisticated novels sometimes miss: a genuine hunger for the sense that one\'s life has a purpose that is waiting to be found, and that the journey toward it, however difficult, is the point.',
