    description: 'Holden Caulfield has just been expelled from Pencey Prep — his fourth school in as many years — and rather than face his parents, he takes a train to New York City and spends three days wandering through it, talking to strangers, visiting old haunts, and thinking about his dead younger brother Allie, his little sister Phoebe, and Jane Gallagher, the girl he played checkers with years ago and never kissed.\n\nSalinger\'s novel is one of the most argued-over in American literature: beloved by generations of teenagers who find in Holden\'s voice an exact articulation of their own alienation, and irritating to at least as many readers who find his self-pity and his repetitive use of the word "phony" exhausting. Both reactions are legitimate, and perhaps both are the point.\n\nWhat the novel does with extraordinary precision is capture the particular pain of adolescent consciousness — the sensitivity to hypocrisy, the desperate tenderness toward innocence, the absolute terror of growing up into a world that seems to require a degree of inauthenticity you cannot yet bring yourself to countenance. Holden\'s fantasy of being the catcher in the rye — standing at the edge of a cliff, catching children before they fall off — is one of the most resonant images in twentieth-century American fiction: a child\'s longing to protect childhood itself from the fall that is coming for everyone.',
