    publisher: 'Harper Collins', isbn: '978-0-06-231609-7',
    description: 'Roughly seventy thousand years ago, something happened to the cognitive architecture of Homo sapiens that changed everything. Harari calls it the Cognitive Revolution, and it is where Sapiens begins: with the moment when our species developed the capacity for language complex enough to discuss things that do not exist — gods, nations, money, corporations — and thereby acquired the ability to cooperate in unlimited numbers. That capacity, he argues, is the key to understanding how we came to dominate the planet.\n\nHarari moves through the Agricultural Revolution, the unification of humanity through trade and empire and religion, the Scientific Revolution, and the Industrial Revolution, always asking the same underlying question: what did all of this mean for the people living through it? His answer is frequently counterintuitive. The Agricultural Revolution, for instance, he characterises not as human progress but as a trap — more food, yes, but harder lives, less varied diets, more disease, and the beginning of social inequality.\n\nSapiens is pop history in the best sense: it synthesises enormous amounts of scholarship into a narrative that is consistently engaging, deliberately provocative, and willing to make arguments that specialists will dispute. Harari writes with clarity and wit, and the book\'s final sections — on happiness, on biotechnology, and on what humanity might become — are among the most thought-provoking pages in recent non-fiction.',
