    description: 'Marcus Aurelius was the most powerful man in the world — Roman Emperor from 161 to 180 CE — and the Meditations are the private notes he wrote to himself, never intended for publication, reminding himself how to live in accordance with the principles of Stoic philosophy. They are a series of exhortations, arguments, and observations, addressed in the second person, as though he needed to remind himself of things he already knew but kept forgetting.\n\nThe Meditations are concerned with a small number of recurring questions: How do I remain rational and compassionate when the world is chaotic and people are frustrating? How do I distinguish between what is in my control and what is not, and focus only on the former? How do I think about death — my own and others\' — without being paralysed by it? How do I do my duty without needing praise for it?\n\nWhat makes the Meditations inexhaustibly readable is the combination of philosophical precision and personal honesty. Marcus is not writing a treatise; he is arguing with himself, trying to close the gap between the person he wants to be and the person he actually is. Two thousand years of readers have found in these notes a practical guide to maintaining equanimity under pressure — not because the philosophy is easy, but because Marcus\'s struggle to practice it is so recognisably human.',
