    description: 'Daniel Kahneman spent decades as a research psychologist, much of it in collaboration with Amos Tversky, systematically documenting the ways in which human reasoning departs from the models of rationality that economists had long assumed. Thinking, Fast and Slow is his attempt to synthesise that work for a general audience, organised around a central metaphor: the mind has two systems.\n\nSystem 1 is fast, automatic, intuitive, and largely unconscious. It makes most of our decisions, forms most of our impressions, and operates below the threshold of deliberate thought. System 2 is slow, effortful, deliberate, and logical — the part of the mind we think of as "thinking," though it is less in control than we assume. Most of the cognitive biases Kahneman describes — the anchoring effect, the availability heuristic, loss aversion, the planning fallacy — arise from System 1 generating answers that System 2 accepts without sufficient scrutiny.\n\nKahneman writes with precision and accessibility, and his examples — drawn from psychology experiments, financial behaviour, medical decision-making, and everyday life — are carefully chosen to produce the experience of recognising one\'s own irrationality in real time. The book is humbling in the best way: a rigorous demonstration that the confidence with which we make judgements bears very little relationship to the accuracy of those judgements, and that knowing this is only the beginning of dealing with it.',
